	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I believe Codemasters lockout defeat is software-controlled.  Color Dreams carts as well, I've seen the source code to it, it's available.  It's pretty cool, it includes modifications for different revisions of NES lockout circuits.  But AFAIK later revision systems put a stop to all of it.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Tue Dec 14, 2010 7:40 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">3gengames wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The games lockout isn't software controlled.....is it? I thought it stunned it via putting some stupid voltage on a pin causing the chip to be retarded. lol.</div>
<br />The typical CIC stun circuits still needed some software to write to a latch to shape the negative voltage pulses coming out of the charge pump. Wisdom Tree's games, released late in the system's life after Nintendo had revised the CIC's input protection a few times, tried about 20 different combinations of frequencies on the two lockout pins that the circuit could control. But for the Super NES, Wisdom Tree just gave up and used a Game Genie/Sonic &amp; Knuckles style lock-on to pass through another game's CIC signals.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
